# Auto Commit + Push After Task Completion

When a coding task is **finished** (feature/fix/docs implemented and verified as needed), **automatically commit and push** without waiting for the user to ask again.

## When to run

- After completing the work the user requested in the current turn (or a clear multi-step task)
- Include related docs/tests/rules that belong to that change
- Skip if there is nothing to commit

## Commit

- Follow the existing git safety protocol (no force push to main/master, no config changes, no secrets)
- Stage only relevant files (exclude bundles, local secrets, unrelated junk)
- Use a concise commit message focused on why
- On Windows PowerShell, pass the message with a here-string if heredoc is unavailable

## Push

- Push the current branch to `origin` (`git push -u origin HEAD` when upstream missing)
- **Retry until success** per `git-push-retry` (backoff on network errors; stop only on auth/non-fast-forward/hook blockers)
- Report final outcome: commit hash + remote branch, or the blocking error

## Do not auto-commit when

- The user explicitly says not to commit/push
- Changes are exploratory drafts the user has not accepted
- Only questions/discussion with no file changes
